  "prompt": "Why do mosquitoes come out in the evening time?",
  "response": "Mosquitoes are most active during the evening and nighttime hours due to their sensitivity to temperature, humidity, and light. During the day, they often seek shelter from the heat and dry air, which can dehydrate them. As the sun sets and the temperature cools down, the air becomes more humid, creating ideal conditions for mosquitoes to emerge and search for food.\n\nAdditionally, many mosquito species are attracted to carbon dioxide and other chemicals produced by humans and animals. As people tend to spend more time outdoors in the evening, especially during the warmer months, mosquitoes take advantage of this opportunity to feed.\n\nThe behavior of mosquitoes also varies by species. Some are more active during the day, while others prefer the evening and night. However, the majority of mosquito species are crepuscular, meaning they are most active during twilight hours, just before sunrise and after sunset.",
